What is much weirder, however, is the callousness with which the App Store =
treats any sort of creative pursuit that is not app development. That may s=
eem like an odd thing to say, given that developers are the most directly i=
mpacted by Apple=E2=80=99s App Store policies, but at the end of the day, t=
he App Store is part of the platform on which developers operate =E2=80=94 =
they are making actual apps, so to some extent it makes sense that if Apple=
 is going to tax someone, it taxes them. Or, to put it in Apple=E2=80=99s p=
referred terms, all of the IP that they develop that they insist on being c=
ompensated for is IP that is directly used by and essential for app develop=
ment.

That is not the case for, say, a YouTuber with a Patreon account, or a writ=
er, or an artist. For any of them to directly benefit from Apple=E2=80=99s =
IP would entail creating an actual app, which is entirely outside their ski=
llset. Instead they go to a platform like Patreon to provide the monetizati=
on and customer management tools that let them monetize their creativity; t=
o the extent there is an app involved, it is being created by Patreon, not =
the individual artists.

The problem, however, is that Apple isn=E2=80=99t charging Patreon, the act=
ual app maker: they are charging creators, by taking 30% of every subscript=
ion. In other words, a $10 subscription made on iOS entails giving $3 to Ap=
ple, and only then 8% to Patreon for their service; the creator ends up wit=
h $6.44 =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, to put it another way, 1,000 true fans ( https:/=
/kk.org/thetechnium/1000-true-fans/ ) is now 1,553 true fans-who-subscribe-=
on-iOS.

That 30% figure is particularly galling, as Nick Heer notes on Pixel Envy (=
 https://pxlnv.com/linklog/patreon-in-app-purchases/ ) :

The 30% fee is also notable. As far as I can tell, only a handful ( https:/=
/graphtreon.com/top-patreon-earners/ ) of Patreon users would exceed the mi=
llion-dollar annual threshold for Apple=E2=80=99s Small Business Program ( =
https://developer.apple.com/app-store/small-business-program/ ). That is, e=
veryone who earns less than a million dollars per year through iOS Patreon =
pledges should, in theory, fork over a 15% commission rate to Apple. But it=
 appears it is Patreon itself which is subject to the 30% rate. Whether tha=
t decision was made by Apple or Patreon, or if it is something which is a c=
onsequence of how App Store billing works, is unclear to me. But one thing =
is true regardless: Apple=E2=80=99s 30% commission is at least double ( htt=
ps://www.patreon.com/pricing ) the rate charged by Patreon itself, and only=
 the latter has any material effect on the relationship between a creative =
professional and their supporters.

In short, Apple is taking a percentage of individual creator subscriptions,=
 but it is treating every individual creator as if they are a subsidiary of=
 Patreon. It=E2=80=99s as if Apple can=E2=80=99t even conceive of the possi=
bility of there being any sort of platform other than themselves; they may =
still market themselves as the company for creators, but their actions sugg=
est they truly don=E2=80=99t care.

The solution I would propose to this issue of platforms on platforms is wha=
t I put forward during the Fanhouse dispute:

As I have documented ( https://stratechery.com/2021/app-store-arguments/?ac=
cess_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubG=
